@node "Usage_Menus" "The Menus"

 @{b}@{fg highlight}The Menus
 ~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   @{b}@{i}@{u}Project@{uu}@{ui}@{ub}

      @{b}@{i}About @{ub}(SHORTCUT: AMIGA + ?)@{ui}

       Opens a requester with some information about the program.
       Compilation date and time are also included here.

      @{b}@{i}Load ReadMe @{ub}(SHORTCUT: AMIGA + L)@{ui}

       Opens a filerequester, where you can select a .readme file,
       that will be loaded, if you submit.
       @{i}@{u}@{b}Note:@{ub}@{uu}@{ui}
         You can also load a readme via Drag'n'Drop !
         Just drag a readme file over the window and let it drop there.
         That's all :)

      @{b}@{i}Iconify @{ub}(SHORTCUT: AMIGA + I)@{ui}

       Resets the program into sleeping mode and minimizes the window.
       That will give you more screen space, if you run your workbench
       in a low resolution.
       When the program is iconified, you will have to select @{b}@{i}Wake up !!!@{ub}@{ui}
       @{i}(SHORTCUT: AMIGA + I)@{ui} from the menu and the windows appears again.
       
      @{b}@{i}Quit @{ub}(SHORTCUT: AMIGA + Q)@{ui}

       Quits the program and frees all used memory.


   @{b}@{i}@{u}Settings@{uu}@{ui}@{ub}

      @{b}@{i}Brainfile@{ub}@{ui}

       Opens the @{"Brainfile" link "Usage_Windows" 46} window (Settings), where
       you can alter the brainfile entries.
       This is useful, if you often upload archives to Aminetź for other people,
       so you don't have always to enter the author and uploader.


   @{b}@{i}@{u}Index List@{uu}@{ui}@{ub}

      @{b}@{i}Update @{ub}(SHORTCUT: AMIGA + U)@{ui}

       Starts @{"wget" link "Require" 0}  to download the actual TREE file from a server of your choice
       (@{"ToolTypes" link "Usage_TTypes" 30}).
       Messages during download will be displayed in the window title of the main window.
       If the download was successful, a filerequester appears, where you can choose
       a directory to save the ARC.NDX file into, that will be the result of the
       conversion, that follows directly.
       If the download failed a requester with an information will appear.

      @{b}@{i}Convert @{ub}(SHORTCUT: AMIGA + C)@{ui}

       Opens a filerequester, where you can select a TREE file from Aminetź. After that,
       you will have to choose the path to save the converted TREE file into as an
       Index List. If the conversion was successful, you will receive a short message -
       and also if it should fail.

      @{b}@{i}Reload @{ub}(SHORTCUT: AMIGA + R)@{ui}

       Reloads the Index List. This is useful, if you have converted a new TREE file,
       that you want to use in ARC at once.


   @{b}@{i}@{u}Help!@{uu}@{ui}@{ub}

      @{b}@{i}How can I... @{ub}(SHORTCUT: AMIGA + H)@{ui}

       Opens the @{"Help" link "Usage_Windows" 83} window, where the different
       items (input fields) are explained.

       @{i}English only at this moment - Translations are available in Aminetź.@{ui}

      @{b}@{i}Main@{ub}@{ui}
      @{b}@{i}General@{ub}@{ui}
      @{b}@{i}Menus@{ub}@{ui}
      @{b}@{i}Windows@{ub}@{ui}
      @{b}@{i}ToolTypes@{ub}@{ui}
      @{b}@{i}Aminetź Index List@{ub}@{ui}

       All these menu items will transfer you into the help system of ARC.
       They point to important help sections, where you can read, if you
       should need some help.

      @{b}@{i}Search@{ub}@{ui}

       If you select this menu item, the @{"search" link "Usage_Windows" 99} window will appear,
       where you can search the whole guide for a query. Useful, if you don't know, where
       to look for into the guide.
@endnode

@node "Usage_Windows" "The Windows"

 @{b}@{fg highlight}The Windows
 ~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   @{b}@{i}@{u}Main@{uu}@{ui}@{ub}

    You can see the main input fields at the left of the window.
    Here you can enter the needed information to create your readme
    and the completely optional fields.

    You have to look for entering the first four topics !
    These are always required (Short, Author, Uploader and
    Type) by Aminetź Style Guide, but only Short is really
    important to create a .readme file. But Style Guide says,
    that the four topics above are recommended, so ARC doesn't
    support such things as only Short in a header.

    Then you have also the possibiliy to
    add an additional description and information of
    your archive and the used language and such things,
    and to add a listing of the contents of the archive
    you want to create the readme file for. But the
    last two topics are optionally and not required
    (additional description and archive info) !

    If you don't know, what the different topics mean
    you can call the online help, where every usable
    topic in the readme header is described (taken from
    aminet doc about uploading and placing archives -
    and slidely modified with comments and headers)

    @{i}read below for more information about online help@{ui}

    At the right of the Type input field, you will find a gadget,
    that contains all possible directory entries, that are allowed
    in Aminetź. How to use this list and how to keep it up-to-date,
    read @{"here" link "Usage_AIL" 0}.

    If you entered all needed items and did your additional stuff,
    then press the "Create ReadMe" button and a filerequester appears,
    where you can select an archive (lha,lzh,run/lzx,jpg,mpg), the
    readme should be created for. If you've done this, just press OK
    and the rest will be done automatically.
    ARC presets an archive in the filerequester, but you can also enter
    a readme filename, BUT if you have selected 'Archive Info'
    and no archive exists, a requester appears and tells you that,
    but it doesn't affect the creation. In this case the archive contents
    listing won't be parsed.


   @{b}@{i}@{u}Brainfile@{uu}@{ui}@{ub}

    The brainfile list should help people, that often upload archives
    for others into Aminetź. So they don't have to enter the uploader
    and author stuff again - they just have to do a few clicks.
    Therefore, just press the button at the right of the uploader
    input field and then just select the entry you need. This
    will be transfered into the input field. How it works:

    Here you can alter the brainfile list. You can add or delete
    a brainfile entry by pressing the right button.
    Or you can also move some entries up or down in the list
    hierarchy.

    If you add an entry, a standard email (please@change.me (XYZ))
    will be added to the list and also be displayed in the string
    input field below the gadget with the different entries.
    You can change the entry here.

    If you want to delete an entry, then select the entry you want
    to delete and press the right button. The entry will be removed
    from the list.

    If you want to move an entry up/down then select the entry to move
    and press the right button.

    If you want to edit an entry, then select the entry to edit and
    change it in the string input field below the list gadget with
    the brainfile entries. If you're done, just press RETURN and
    the changes can be seen at once.

    You can now immediatly save the altered list or just use this new
    list in the program. If you've altered the list and didn't save it,
    you will be asked if you want to save, when you want to exit the
    program.


   @{b}@{i}@{u}Help@{uu}@{ui}@{ub}

    In this window, you can find an extract of the Aminetź upload
    instructions. You can scroll the contents with the scroller at
    the right of the ListView gadget.
    If you want to close the window, just click on the closegadget.


   @{b}@{i}@{u}Popup@{uu}@{ui}@{ub}

    Usage of the popupmenu window is really simple.
    If you select an item from the list, it will be used for the
    field it belongs to. If you don't want to select anything from
    list, then just @{b}press the RIGHT mousebutton and the window closes@{ub}
    @{b}without following actions or changes@{ub}.


   @{b}@{i}@{u}Search Guide@{uu}@{ui}@{ub}

    You can enter a query in the input field at the top of the window here. If you
    click on the checkbox below, the case sensitive search will be activated. You'll
    have to take care, that you've entered the query right ! This search mode is a
    little bit faster than the other. If you want to start the search, just click
    on the Search button. After a little delay, the results will appear in the listview
    below the Search button. If there are no entries, nothing has matched you query.
    Just enter another query and start the search again. If something was found
    it will be displayed. Then just select the entry you want to look into, and the
    guide appears on your screen. If you're done, just click the CLOSEGADGET and the
    window closes and you can continue your work.
@endnode

@node "Usage_TTypes" "The TOOLTYPES"

 @{b}@{fg highlight}The TOOLTYPES
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   @{i}- EDITOR@{ui}
       Let's you change the preset from C:Ed to your
       favourite editor.
   @{i}- AUTHOR@{ui}
       Let's you preset a string, that will be displayed
       in the Author string gadget after startup.
   @{i}- UPLOADER@{ui}
       Same as above for the Uploader string gadget.
   @{i}- PATH@{ui}
       Let's you specify a default path, that will be
       used instantly.
   @{i}- NOCOPY@{ui}
       If you've activated this tooltype, the copyright
       notice will be suppressed in the output of any
       readme file.
   @{i}- FOOTER@{ui}
       If you've set this variable with the full path
       of the signature file to add, it will be added
       to every readme you create.
       If you want to know now, what happens with such
       a generated readme if you load it, then I can
       tell you: the added signature will be stripped out
       while loading. Therefore ARC adds one single line
       before the signature, that contains -F-. That's
       all :)
   @{i}- SERVER@{ui}
       Here you can enter a server site, that you want to
       connect, if you want to download and update your
       Index List via Internet.
       An example is included into the icon ToolTypes of ARC.
       Be sure to enter the complete path / url with file (TREE) !

       If you are confused, why I have entered an Aminetź
       mirror site, that doesn't contain a full mirrored
       Aminetź (ftp.uni-erlangen.de), then try to connect
       to ftp.uni-paderborn.de and you will see, that the
       login validation takes a lot of time. So I decided
       to enter ftp.uni-erlangen.de, that is much faster !


   All tooltypes already exists in the tooltypes list of
   ARC icon. EDITOR is disabled by (). The two others are
   enabled as an example. PATH is disabled, so you have to
   set it, if you want to use it. NOCOPY is disabled (default).
   FOOTER is also disabled. And even SERVER. Change, if you want :)
@endnode

@node "Usage_AIL" "Aminetź Index List"

 @{b}@{fg highlight}The Aminetź Index List
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}


   The Aminetź Index List helps you to select a drawer,
   that exists into Aminetź and where your archive should
   placed into. If you want to know why, then look at the
   number of possible directories :)

   So you have 3 different ways to keep your Aminetź Index
   List up-to-date:

   1. The easiest way would be to convert a Aminetź TREE
      file, that you can find on any Aminet CD, but just
      take the newer ones for updates :)
      How to convert such a TREE file, you can read @{"here" link "Usage_Menus" 51}.

   2. Like 1., using @{"update" link "Usage_Menus" 42} from menu.

   3. You list the directory structure of an Aminetź CD
      into a file using the dir command of the workbench.
      
      @{u}Example:@{uu}
             Dir CD0:Aminet/ ALL DIRS >Sys:Utilities/ARC.NDX

      @{b}Attention !@{ub} This list has to be placed in the same
                  drawer, where ARC is !

      @{b}Note also, that you have to remove the new, recent and the@{ub}
      @{b}info drawers, if you do this !@{ub}


   @{i}An example list is included in this archive !
   (Last updated: 02-Feb-99)@{ui}

   If everything went well, you can use this list immediately
   choosing @{"Reload" link "Usage_Menus" 58} from the Index List menu.

   There are also some special features !
   If you enter something in the Type input field, it will
   be automatically checked, if the given directory exists
   in the list (if a list exists). If that's not given,
   a requester appears, that informs you about that.

   Same procedure, if you load a readme.

   Why did I add this feature ? Well, i was unable to
   remember all the possible combinations of drawers,
   that are used in the very fast growing Aminetź.
   That's it - just to make life easier :)
@endnode

@node "Usage_Help" "The HELP system"

 @{b}@{fg highlight}The HELP system
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}


   If you should need some help at any time, just press the @{b}HELP@{ub}
   key on your keyboard and the guide file will be displayed, if you have
   installed it !

   Also look into the @{"Help!" link "Usage_Menus" 64} menu, where important hot links are available,
   that will transfer you to different points of this documentation !
   A @{"search" link "Usage_Windows" 99} engine is also available !
@endnode
